<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Bobby on 11-16-1999 09:23 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Well, I thought you'd come to the CPU cycle stuff. Sure you can only implement what the computer is able to handle in a reasonable amount of time and won't frustrate the gaming experience. E.g. in your lights example it shouldn't happen that while your character is walking around, things start to get jerky as the AI dedicates to movement paths for switching off the lights. I had this experience in JA2 (I know its getting kind of old) where the cow movements temporarily froze the game. The same sort of freezing happened when too many objects (e.g. people) where moving around.

This said: Rather than just stick to a AI implementation that together with other routines satisfies the minimum computer requirements, why no determine a gamer's CPU power and enable other AI routines and/or extend existing AI routines as CPU power permits?
Also, if it seems that it might throw off game balance if combat AI were involved, why not just exclude that aspect from the AI enhancements.
Some of the benefits would be:
I can play the game X years after its release with a new computer and experience all the cool things my older computer couldn't handle (assuming new platforms and computers stay compatible with old ones).
A gamer expecting a lot from his/her new computer will get what he/she wants (at least from the AI perspective).
A gamer with a "shitty" computer will still be able to play the game (while more demanding games won't be an option), expecting no fancy stuff (or he/she would have most likely bought a new computer).</TEXTAREA>
